SIMPLE: patriarchal
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patriarchal
<hw>Pa`tri*ar"chal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>patriarcal</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a
patriarch or to patriarchs; possessed by, or subject to, patriarchs;
<as>as, <ex>patriarchal</ex> authority or jurisdiction; a
<ex>patriarchal</ex> see; a <ex>patriarchal</ex> church.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characteristic of a patriarch; venerable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>About whose <qex>patriarchal</qex> knee⟦br⟧
Late the little children clung.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>Having an organization of
society and government in which the head of the family exercises
authority over all its generations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Patriarchal cross</b></col> <fld>(Her.)</fld>, <cd>a
cross, the shaft of which is intersected by two transverse beams, the
upper one being the smaller. See <xex>Illust.</xex> (2) of
<er>Cross</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Patriarchal dispensation</b></col>,
<cd>the divine dispensation under which the patriarchs lived before the
law given by Moses.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1052 --></p>

<p><ent>Patriarchate</ent>⟦br⟧
